Kowloon is a terraced delta city built where the Jhen River empties into Coppersalt Bay, north of the continent. Before the city existed, the delta was called the Shallow Thousand — nine miles of stilts, prayer poles, tide farms, and contraband docks where clan skiffs moved by moon and bell, not by law. The Lampkeepers, solitary hermits tending oil beacons for navigators without asking payment, provided the philosophical seed of Kowloon's later civic neutrality. The Ashfall Monsoon — three consecutive years of volcanic rain from the Cinderteeth Mountains — destroyed the delta settlements and killed six hundred in Yen-Mak in a single night. Six surviving houses convened on a basalt outcrop and created the Neon Covenant: one wall, one law; one ledger, one ration code; one square, final judgment. The Covenant's name comes from phosphorescent squid-dye ink that glowed under torchlight, proving the document had not been altered in darkness. Five civic institutions now govern: Harbor Syndics (docks, tariffs, licensing), Jade Magistracy (tax, civil law, emergency rationing — their jade seal weighs forty pounds and requires two magistrates to carry, preventing single-official emergency power invocation), Temple Circle (healing, sanctuaries, oath arbitration), Wardens of Iron (walls, gates, city militia), and Courier Lantern Office (registry, post routes, census). The city's color-coding is civic shorthand readable by residents at a glance: crimson for emergency authority, jade for licensed commerce, gold for bonded merchants, blue for harbor infrastructure, violet for sanctioned ambiguity, cyan for flood and rainwater systems.

